[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(8) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Statutes of the heathen . . . and of the kings of Israel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The national guilt was twofold. It comprised: (1) idolatry in the strict sense—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " worship of other gods than Jehovah; (2) a heathenish mode of worshipping Jehovah Himself—namely, under the form of a bullock, as Jeroboam I. had ordained. The term “statutes” means religious rules or ordinances. (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 12:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “statutes;” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 20:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “manners;” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 3:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “ordinance.”)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which they had made—i.e., the statutes which the kings of Israel had made. (Comp. 2Kings 17:19 b.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Which they had made",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "i.e.,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " the statutes which the kings of Israel had made. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Kings 17:19",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "b.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ")",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:8-9",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 17:8-9",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And walked in the statutes of the heathen — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "According to their laws and customs in the worship of their Baals, and other of their sins. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And of the kings of Israel, which ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "statutes ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they had made — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Had ordained concerning the worship of the calves, and against their going up to Jerusalem to worship. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And the children of Israel did secretly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — This belongs, either, 1st, To their gross idolatries, and other abominable practices, which they were ashamed to own before others; or, 2d, To the worship of the calves, and so the words are otherwise rendered, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "They covered things that were not right toward the Lord: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "they covered their idolatrous worship of the calves with fair pretences of necessity, the two kingdoms being now divided, and at enmity; and of their honest intention of serving the true God, and retaining the substance of the Jewish religion. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "From the tower of the watchmen to the fenced city — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In all parts and places, both in cities and in the country; yea, in the most uninhabited parts, where few or none dwelt besides the watch-men, who were left there in towers, to preserve the cattle and fruits of the earth, or to give notice of the approach of enemies.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "17:7-23 Though the destruction of the kingdom of the ten tribes was but briefly related, it is in these verses largely commented upon, and the reasons of it given. It was destruction from the Almighty: the Assyrian was but the rod of his anger, Isa 10:5. Those that bring sin into a country or family, bring a plague into it, and will have to answer for all the mischief that follows. And vast as the outward wickedness of the world is, the secret sins, evil thoughts, desires, and purposes of mankind are much greater. There are outward sins which are marked by infamy; but ingratitude, neglect, and enmity to God, and the idolatry and impiety which proceed therefrom, are far more malignant. Without turning from every evil way, and keeping God's statutes, there can be no true godliness; but this must spring from belief of his testimony, as to wrath against all ungodliness and unrighteousness, and his mercy in Christ Jesus.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Idolatry was worse in the Israelites than in other nations, since it argued not merely folly and a gross carnal spirit, but also black ingratitude ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 20:2-3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The writer subdivides the idolatries of the Israelites into two classes, pagan and native - those which they adopted from the nations whom they drove out, and those which their own kings imposed on them. Under the former head would come the great mass of the idolatrous usages described in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:9-11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; \"the high places\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the \"images\" and \"groves\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the causing of their children to \"pass through the fire\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and the \"worship of the host of heaven\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : under the latter would fall the principal points in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 17:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
