  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And walked in the statutes of the heathen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The\" statutes of the heathen\" are their customs and observances, especially in matters of religion. The Israelites had been repeatedly warned not to follow these (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 18:3, 30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 12:29-31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 18:9-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Whom the Lord east out from before the children of Israel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the Canaanitish nations, whose idolatries and other \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "abominations\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " were particularly hateful to God (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 18:26-29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 20:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 29:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 32:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and of the kings of Israel.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The sins and idolatries of Israel had a double origin. The great majority were derived from the heathen nations with whom they were brought into contact, and were adopted voluntarily by the people themselves. Of this kind were the worship at \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "high",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " places\" (ver. 9), the \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "images\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and \"groves\" (ver. 10), the causing of their children to \"pass through the fire\" (ver. 17), the employment of divination and enchantments (ver. 17), and perhaps the \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "worship",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the host of heaven\" (ver. 16). A certain number, however, came in from a different source, being imposed upon the people by their kings. To this class belong the desertion of the temple-worship, enforced by Jeroboam (vex. 21), the setting up of the calves at Dan and Bethel (ver. 16) by the same, and the Baal and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Astarte",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " worship (ver. 16), introduced by Ahab. This last and worst idolatry was not established without a good deal of persecution, as we learn from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 18:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Which they had made.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 2 Kings 17:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
